I figure it will take time to develop a consensus on how python tests should be written.
So I'm going to have this py2 dir for now.
Code is in sync with the refactored h2o1 python
It has the new -uc/--usecloud parameter (which also can be pass in a config json file) to connect to a prebuilt cloud but it also supports all the cloud build methodologies of the h2o1 cloud building/logging (multijvm/multinode/single jvm etc)

All the normal logs in sandbox
Just put the minimal library modules in to get a test to pass, and only changed what was needed  to get cloud build working

Only supports get_cloud to h2o

this test passes with hacks around stuff I mentioned in email (at least like this, I didn't try multinode or with a config json or with -uc/--usecloud but that works in h2o1, so should just work here)

 cd py2/testdir_single_jvm
 python test_simple.py

You can example that file, and see the new h2o.init() which takes the same params as before, but does all the decisionmaking about existing clouds, creating clouds, parameters to h2o etc, outside of the test (no if decided_if_localhost)

h2o.py is a placeholder for indirecting to other files. I think it general tests will be modified to not require any additional stuff there (i.e. point to the new file directly)...but will see what feels right.

Ray has plans for how to expand h2o_methods.py to get autogen for h2o request params and returned json object.
All h2o requests are considered methods hanging off of h2o.nodes (which is really h2o_nodes.nodes)

So the concept, like h2o1, is a collection of nodes, which have some state (mostly reflecting how the java -jar was started..params..but other catchall state dumped in to). ....and then there are methods on the base H2O defintion

The full collection of objects (like h2o1) are: RemoteHost (only used if building multi-node with config json), LocalH2O, RemoteH2O, and ExternalH2O. These are all the same as h2o1.

Depending on what kind of node object you are, you have some method differences (same as h2o1)

I'm thinking I'll also have h2o_cmd() like before, for optional use, which is a functional api that calles the node level methods. (like existing h2o_cmd.runRF)

Note our R package already introduces a functional api that's different than the h2o node api (it tries to track existing R packages).

I did a copy/paste of some h2o methods ray had done by hand into h2o_ray.py ..wanted to play with them without messing up ray
I'll stay in sync with whatever he moves to, (autogen will change all that anyhow). at the very least it allows experimentation with managing the h2o methods as separate file.
I dropped some of my from * import * stuff to just import the full module to get rid of some circular import issues.

on utf8 test, I eliminated the chars 0x00 thru 0x1d. When they show up in 'domains' after parse, the json seems to not decode. I used to use those control characters in h2o, so not sure why a problem. Maybe h2o didn't have 'domains' for enums where I was looking post-parse. The only interesting chars in that range are probably CR and LF, and we don't allow embedded CR/LF in enums, so maybe don't care.

Cliff had pushed a fix for windows, that isn't enough to keep Linux working. This fixes that and hopefully keeps it right for Cliff.
psutil psopen wants a args list, if you don't want to also run /bin/sh to interpret a string, when starting a process. This was fine when h2o.jar supported -param=value, for how I create the args list, but with space..i.e. "-port 54333'...the two values want to be different args. Windows can always take a string, Unix only takes a string if you also /bin/sh. Wanted to avoid that. There are rules for combining an args list to a string for Windows, but with Cliff's case it looks like we don't want to rely on the rules and join the string ourselves. But keep the args list on unix/mac/linux, to avoid /bin/sh (seems silly to run /bin/sh). So I create the args list right for unix, and " ".join() it for windows. This depends on this detection in h2o_test.py which I think works (didn't test on cygwin/windows but maybe Cliff can see if things still work)

h2o_test.py
The re.match should hit all cases of cygwin and windows
        pf = platform.system()
        print "System is %s" % pf
        cmd = self.get_args()
        if re.match('win', pf, re.IGNORECASE): # covers cygwin and windows
            cmd = " ".join(cmd)
        spawn = spawn_cmd(logPrefix, cmd=cmd, capture_output=self.capture_output)

Added CC-Nanotrasen, an IRC bot made by Skibiliano and given to us by him under CC-BY-SA 3.0 licensing
WHAT DOES THIS MEAN? It means all servers running this SVN now have the option to use an easy to configure IRC bot capable of relaying adminhelps from ingame to the server/channel of their choice.
- Runs on python 2.6 scripts with psyco support
- Relaying can be toggled from config.txt (so you don't runtime with every adminhelp if you decide not to use it)
- Comes with a bunch of other useful and fun tools too
- Added a new global proc, send2irc(msg,msg2) YOU'LL NEVER GUESS WHAT IT DOES CONSIDERING WHAT I JUST MENTIONED
----msg and msg2 are just what text gets relayed to irc, separated by a |, for instance send2irc(hello, world) would come out as
"CC_NanoTrasen: Hello | World

Signed-off-by: Lee moon soo <moon@apache.org>

- We switched Rekall to a new, more stable renderer model. This
means you have to use new clients or Rekall will not work. The
clients included in the server.deb 0.3-2 are already up to date.

- We completely removed Volatility in this release. Rekall is now
feature equivalent and just works much better so this was the
logical choice.

- We made many improvements to the SqliteDataStore, feel free to
give it a try.

- There is also a new remote data store. This datastore connects
via HTTP to one or more data servers which in turn can store the
actual data using any of the existing data stores. Currently we
support sharding between the data servers and basic rebalancing
by size of the stored data. This is still experimental but
preliminary results are very promising.

- We added labeling of clients to the gui. You can now chose some
clients from the search page, give them a label, and the run
hunts just on that group of clients. This also changes the format
how GRR stores user labels!!! This means that you have to relabel
your user accounts or use one of the console scripts we provide.

- As always there are lots of bug fixes. We fixed the race
condition which errors with "No valid status message" as an
example but there are many more.

Another code push. As always there are many bugfixes to many
parts of the code. Notable changes:

- There are some UI improvements (more usage of AngularJS!).
- The export of results is now using softlinks to deduplicate
  data. Export is possible as .tar and .zip.
- We have more efficient collections (to store for example hunt
  results). Those are also used for hunt logs + errors so the UI
  for those should be faster for large hunts

Note that we do not ship precompiled protobuf files anymore
starting with this commit. You need to run make in the grr/proto/
directory to create those files. If you use setup.py, it will do
it for you.

Also, starting from this release, we will use Github as the main
repository and remove the one on code.google.com.

- Updating the UI libraries.
- Making the UI work with Django >= 1.7
- Fixing the problem with labels and MySQL.

- Fix https://github.com/google/grr/issues/93 by adding some new artifacts to
  the skip list until people have a chance to upgrade clients.
- Change client packaging and fix init scripts so that the .deb can be installed
  on debian as well as ubuntu.
- Make storage more efficient by using unversioned streams.
- Enable journalling on collections for better reliability.
- Add status logging collections for hunt output plugins to help debugging
  export plugin problems.
- Fix worker monitoring problem where errors weren't converted to strings.

Making GRR work with the latest Rekall release, improving the
performance for Well Known Flows, and some small bugfixes.

Remove enroller. Bump versions. Fix artifact bug.

- Remove the enroller server-side component. This is now handled by the worker.
  You may need to update any custom init scripts you're using to launch this
  component.
- Bump client version to 3.0.0.5 and server to 0.3.0-5 to be in sync with the
  client version.  (Note we skipped a couple of numbers here).
- Add artifact HTTP API
- Fix a bug with artifact users.* knowledgebase interpolation
- Improvements to windows signing script
- Remove unused Worker.task_limit config option
- Change Worker.queue_shards default to 5

Fix hunt pause bug. Separate different queues.

- Separate queue names into enrollment, flows, hunts, stats
- Fix bug with hunt pausing where clients scheduled in the future due to a
  client rate limit would continue to pick up and run the hunt at the scheduled
  time even if it had been paused. Pause is now effective at stopping
  new clients from being scheduled for the hunt. More hunt control changes are
  planned, see https://github.com/google/grr/issues/106.
- Change install script to require root so people can setup proxy environment
  variables easily.

Randomize start time of system cronjobs.

- Use rekall json renderer
- More work splitting out queues

Fix cron bug, add OS X vagrant

- Fix cron randomization bug introduced in last commit.
- Add OS X vagrant config and provision script.
- Disable worker http monitoring by default to make it easier to start multiple
  workers (avoid port conflicts).

Datastore cleanup:
- Adding a test that forces all data store implementations to exactly
implement the API defined by the base class.
- Adding a test for the limit functionality so all implementations
actually adhere to limits.
- Getting rid of the name "predicate" wherever possible which we used
interchangeably with attribute.
- Removing the DeleteAttributesRegex function from the data store API
since we only use it in a single place for setting up tests and
implementing this function for each datastore is some work. (Thanks to
Sean for the hint that this method is not really useful!)
NFS, config parsing/artifact work, angular update

Bug fixes, temporarily remove minicomm.

- Fix race condition bug in MultiGetFile
- Fix some broken tests
- Change audit log to rollover every couple of weeks so it is usable in the gui.
  Fix server usage stats.
- Temporarily remove minicomm, it isn't submitted internally yet and we need to
  sync up the repos to bring in some outside changes. It will come back in the
  next sync.

Large code cleanup and bugfix push:

- Protobuf performance improvements
- Fixed bug where processlist regex was ignored
  (https://github.com/google/grr/issues/184)
- Fixed filefinder bug with files in root dir
- Added ability to search for file permissions to the client
- New clients will appear faster in search results (previously waiting for
interrogate to finish)
- Hovering over a time value will give you a human friendly "x days ago" tooltip
- Fixed a bug where a weird filesystem (bootable CD) broke UI listdirectory VFS
buttons
- Added flow status, and user settings API (see API docs in UI)
- Large code cleanup of imports: moving towards "import what you use":
- No longer import server_plugins into tests within grr/lib.
- No longer do mass imports in several "__init__.py" files.
-- Mass imports moved to corresponding "registry_init.py" files, so they can
still be used when necessary.
- Move some classes around to avoid circular dependency of modules:
-- Shifting around of several artifact classes, including moving
ArtifactRegistry to its own module.
-- Move FlowRunnerArgs to flow_runner.py.
-- Collapse rdfvalues/checks.py into checks/checks.py

Make rdfvalue dependency structure explicit.

- Remove call to globals() from rdfvalue.py.
- Redirect references to rdf classes to the file of definition. Minor changes to
  avoid dependency loops.
- FindFiles client action is now 15% faster. Added a benchmark to prove it.
- AFF4 directory index creation is now not done when we are sure the object
  already exists. This helps to remove some of the data base load in the front
  end.
- Fix failure to read special files in /proc/

Implement datastore cleanup.

- Implemented DeletionPool object to optimize deletion of large amounts of
  objects.
- Now objects can implement OnDelete() method if they need to delete dependent
  objects. They should use DeletionPool (a large cache, essentially) for a
  more efficient deletion process.
- Implemented OnDelete for GRRHunts - so that they delete symlinks to hunts
  flows.
- Implemented CleanHunts and CleanCronJobs cron jobs that delete old hunts and
  old cron-inititated flows respectively. DataRetention.cron_jobs_flows_ttl,
  DataRetention.hunts_ttl and DataRetention.hunts_ttl_exception_label config
  options are used to configure them. Currently these jobs are turned off by
  default.
- More config checks, parsers
- Fixes to windows client build that caused missing labels, bring scripts up to
  modern rekall and protobuf
- More work on minicomm C++ client
- Add VFS chroot to allow clients to operate relative to a different root

- Adding the notion of a VFS virtual root to clients.
- Making RSA bit sizes configurable.
- Fixing an XSS bug in the api.

FEATURE (Dashboard): New version of SeaClouds Dashboard (v2)

This new version is AngularJS based, rewriten from the scratch in order to improve the overall quality of the Dashboard. It follows the design guidelines exposed in D4.5.

Thanks to @rosogon for the work done on the topology editor/viewer and to @mbarrientos for helping me with bugfixes and cosmetic improvements

FEATURE(designer): Implements a designer view to enter the cloud credentials.

This commit adds a view to enter the credentials. It also contains code to generate a topology from a DAM, and to inject the credentials into a DAM. Thanks to @rosogon for the Credential Editor.

Adds specification of frontend node in the designer.

A frontend node is specified in the topology as a boolean property in
the properties of a node. Visually, it appears with black rounded line.
The rest of nodes appears with a grey rounded line. Only one frontend
node can be specified.

This way of specifying a frontend has less priority than the previous
one when generating the AAM (set the frontend node in the
app_requirements element), but it is easier to implement from the designer.

Form code for the topology editor has been moved from editor.js to
editor-forms.js, as the former file was too complex.
